            "title": "Clinical pharmacokinetics of neuromuscular relaxants in pregnancy.",
            "abstract": "Despite an increased in bodyweight, plasma volume by 45% and blood volume by 35% that might influence the volume of distribution of polar drugs, the apparent volume of distribution at steady state (Vss), volume of distribution (Vd) and the apparent volume of the central compartment (Vc) of atracurium, vecuronium and pancuronium are unchanged during pregnancy. With an elimination that is independent of renal, hepatic and enzymatic functions, the clearance of atracurium is also unchanged. This is corroborated by an unchanged clinical duration of atracurium during pregnancy. The clearance of pancuronium is increased by 27% during caesarean section. This may be explained by the increased glomerular filtration rate reported in pregnant women. The clinical duration of vecuronium in term and postpartum women is twice that reported in nonpregnant women. On the other hand, an increase in the clearance clearance of vecuronium during cesarean sections has been reported. The umbilical/maternal vei",
